Most US / Western analysts presumably mean well when they talk about the human rights of minorities in India but are genuinely naive in their understanding of the ground realities. The friction points of majority vs minority issues in India can best be appreciated with the following scenarios / Qs being posed in the context of the US.

1. Will Uncle Sam allow schools that teach hatred of the USA & brainwash students to sabotage the USA from within? Several Madrasas in India do that.
2. Will the US nationalize operations of & donations to Churches, yet give freedom of operations to Jewish & Hindu Temples, Muslim mosques, etc., offer salaries to the employees of such minority institutions but NOT to the employees of Churches, and distribute some of the donations to the Churches to mosques & temples (but not the other way around? This happens in many states in India.
3. Will the US laws allow different civil laws for minorities depending on their religion? E.g. will a US Muslim be allowed not to have to pay alimony because his religion says so? Will US civil laws allow a Muslim to have up to 4 wives because his religion allows it? OR should the civil laws be the same for all US citizens & permanent residents irrespective of their religion? Happens in India.
4. Will the US Govt pay for minorities to visit religious shrines in other countries but not do the same for its own majority population? This happens in India for Muslims going for the Haaj to Saudi Arabia - even most Muslim nations do not do this.
5. Will the US allow only minorities (non-Christian) to run religion-based schools but prohibit the majority (Christians) from running academic institutions? This too happens in India.
6. Will the USA allow descendants of Western Europe to teach their own version of history claiming that they once ruled the US, that it is their right to rule the US again, that they owe allegiance to past European rulers and not to the current democratic America? Many Muslims in India do so even if they are not even descendants of the foreign invaders. In fact, behind most Muslims of India are the forced conversions, killings of their forefathers, and rapes of their ancestor women but Madrasas teach them false history.
7. Does the US not have different pathways & timelines for immigrants with different backgrounds (refugees/asylum seekers, highly educated, laborers, relatives of citizens, etc.)? If Christians were a minority in Mexico & Canada and abused/harassed because of their religion, would the US not give them an accelerated pathway toward immigration & citizenship?

Why should the answers/remedies of India to similar issues be different from those of the USA? Both are democratic & secular countries.

Thinking that India needs different solutions to these Qs than the US is the real issue here that most well-meaning yet naive analysts do not understand.

Insisting that India has communal issues because the US & the West does not understand real issues & their nuances is downright arrogant, delusional & condescending.

Narendra Modi is only as much a Hindu Nationalist leader as, say Donald Trump or Joe Biden are Christian Nationalist leaders of the US.

If & when the Muslim population exceeds 10-20% in the US, Uncle Sam will be dealing with the same issues that India is dealing with for decades. So, US & western media, in general, need to wake up & stop sounding like broken records of "copy-paste" journalism. Instead, learn from India's experiences & empathize.

The friction points of majority vs minority issues in India can best be appreciated with the following scenarios / Qs being posed in the context of the US.

1. Will Uncle Sam allow schools that teach hatred of the USA & brainwash students to sabotage the USA from within? Several Madrasas in India do that.
2. Will the US nationalize operations of & donations to Churches, yet give freedom of operations to Jewish & Hindu Temples, Muslim mosques, etc., offer salaries to the employees of such minority institutions but NOT to the employees of Churches, and distribute some of the donations to the Churches to mosques & temples (but not the other way around? This happens in many states in India.
3. Will the US laws allow different civil laws for minorities depending on their religion? E.g. will a US Muslim be allowed not to have to pay alimony because his religion says so? Will US civil laws allow a Muslim to have up to 4 wives because his religion allows it? OR should the civil laws be the same for all US citizens & permanent residents irrespective of their religion? Happens in India.
4. Will the US Govt pay for minorities to visit religious shrines in other countries but not do the same for its own majority population? This happens in India for Muslims going for the Haaj to Saudi Arabia - even most Muslim nations do not do this.
5. Will the US allow only minorities (non-Christian) to run religion-based schools but prohibit the majority (Christians) from running academic institutions? This too happens in India.
6. Will the USA allow descendants of Western Europe to teach their own version of history claiming that they once ruled the US, that it is their right to rule the US again, that they owe allegiance to past European rulers and not to the current democratic America? Many Muslims in India do so even if they are not even descendants of the foreign invaders. In fact, behind most Muslims of India are the forced conversions, killings of their forefathers, and rapes of their ancestor women but Madrasas teach them false history.
7. Does the US not have different pathways & timelines for immigrants with different backgrounds (refugees/asylum seekers, highly educated, laborers, relatives of citizens, etc.)? If Christians were a minority in Mexico & Canada and abused/harassed because of their religion, would the US not give them an accelerated pathway toward immigration & citizenship?

Why should the answers/remedies of India to similar issues be different from those of the USA? Both are democratic & secular countries.

Thinking that India needs different solutions to these Qs than the US is the real issue here that most well-meaning yet naive analysts do not understand.

Most US / Western analysts presumably mean well when they talk about the human rights of minorities in India but are genuinely naive in their understanding of the ground realities. The friction points of majority vs minority issues in India can best be appreciated with the following scenarios / Qs being posed in the context of the US.

1. Will Uncle Sam allow schools that teach hatred of the USA & brainwash students to sabotage the USA from within? Several Madrasas in India do that.
2. Will the US nationalize operations of & donations to Churches, yet give freedom of operations to Jewish & Hindu Temples, Muslim mosques, etc., offer salaries to the employees of such minority institutions but NOT to the employees of Churches, and distribute some of the donations to the Churches to mosques & temples (but not the other way around? This happens in many states in India.
3. Will the US laws allow different civil laws for minorities depending on their religion? E.g. will a US Muslim be allowed not to have to pay alimony because his religion says so? Will US civil laws allow a Muslim to have up to 4 wives because his religion allows it? OR should the civil laws be the same for all US citizens & permanent residents irrespective of their religion? Happens in India.
4. Will the US Govt pay for minorities to visit religious shrines in other countries but not do the same for its own majority population? This happens in India for Muslims going for the Haaj to Saudi Arabia - even most Muslim nations do not do this.
5. Will the US allow only minorities (non-Christian) to run religion-based schools but prohibit the majority (Christians) from running academic institutions? This too happens in India.
6. Will the USA allow descendants of Western Europe to teach their own version of history claiming that they once ruled the US, that it is their right to rule the US again, that they owe allegiance to past European rulers and not to the current democratic America? Many Muslims in India do so even if they are not even descendants of the foreign invaders. In fact, behind most Muslims of India are the forced conversions, killings of their forefathers, and rapes of their ancestor women but Madrasas teach them false history.
7. Does the US not have different pathways & timelines for immigrants with different backgrounds (refugees/asylum seekers, highly educated, laborers, relatives of citizens, etc.)? If Christians were a minority in Mexico & Canada and abused/harassed because of their religion, would the US not give them an accelerated pathway toward immigration & citizenship?

Why should the answers/remedies of India to similar issues be different from those of the USA? Both are democratic & secular countries.

Thinking that India needs different solutions to these Qs than the US is the real issue here that most well-meaning yet naive analysts do not understand.

Insisting that India has communal issues because the US & the West does not understand real issues & their nuances is downright arrogant, delusional & condescending.

Narendra Modi is only as much a Hindu Nationalist leader as, say Donald Trump or Joe Biden are Christian Nationalist leaders of the US.

If & when the Muslim population exceeds 10-20% in the US, Uncle Sam will be dealing with the same issues that India is dealing with for decades. So, US & western media, in general, need to wake up & stop sounding like broken records of "copy-paste" journalism. Instead, learn from India's experiences & empathize.

Most US / Western analysts presumably mean well when they talk about the human rights of minorities in India but are genuinely naive in their understanding of the ground realities. The friction points of majority vs minority issues in India can best be appreciated with the following scenarios / Qs being posed in the context of the US.

1. Will Uncle Sam allow schools that teach hatred of the USA & brainwash students to sabotage the USA from within? Several Madrasas in India do that.
2. Will the US nationalize operations of & donations to Churches, yet give freedom of operations to Jewish & Hindu Temples, Muslim mosques, etc., offer salaries to the employees of such minority institutions but NOT to the employees of Churches, and distribute some of the donations to the Churches to mosques & temples (but not the other way around? This happens in many states in India.
3. Will the US laws allow different civil laws for minorities depending on their religion? E.g. will a US Muslim be allowed not to have to pay alimony because his religion says so? Will US civil laws allow a Muslim to have up to 4 wives because his religion allows it? OR should the civil laws be the same for all US citizens & permanent residents irrespective of their religion? Happens in India.
4. Will the US Govt pay for minorities to visit religious shrines in other countries but not do the same for its own majority population? This happens in India for Muslims going for the Haaj to Saudi Arabia - even most Muslim nations do not do this.
5. Will the US allow only minorities (non-Christian) to run religion-based schools but prohibit the majority (Christians) from running academic institutions? This too happens in India.
6. Will the USA allow descendants of Western Europe to teach their own version of history claiming that they once ruled the US, that it is their right to rule the US again, that they owe allegiance to past European rulers and not to the current democratic America? Many Muslims in India do so even if they are not even descendants of the foreign invaders. In fact, behind most Muslims of India are the forced conversions, killings of their forefathers, and rapes of their ancestor women but Madrasas teach them false history.
7. Does the US not have different pathways & timelines for immigrants with different backgrounds (refugees/asylum seekers, highly educated, laborers, relatives of citizens, etc.)? If Christians were a minority in Mexico & Canada and abused/harassed because of their religion, would the US not give them an accelerated pathway toward immigration & citizenship?

Why should the answers/remedies of India to similar issues be different from those of the USA? Both are democratic & secular countries.

Thinking that India needs different solutions to these Qs than the US is the real issue here that most well-meaning yet naive analysts do not understand.

Insisting that India has communal issues because the US & the West does not understand real issues & their nuances is downright arrogant, delusional & condescending.

Narendra Modi is only as much a Hindu Nationalist leader as, say Donald Trump or Joe Biden are Christian Nationalist leaders of the US.

If & when the Muslim population exceeds 10-20% in the US, Uncle Sam will be dealing with the same issues that India is dealing with for decades. So, US & western media, in general, need to wake up & stop sounding like broken records of "copy-paste" journalism. Instead, learn from India's experiences & empathize.
